Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR TO ERLANG GENERATOR - Production Translation Backend
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Generates idiomatic Erlang code from HIR (High-level Intermediate Representation)
Note: Produces: module declarations, functions, pattern matching, guards,
Note: concurrent primitives, message passing, receive blocks
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa"
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/erlang/erlang_printer.runa" as ErlangPrinter
Note: erlang_parser import removed in P2-F Round 2C - it was a dead frontend
Note: dependency (only the import line existed; no references anywhere in this
Note: file). hir_to_erlang.runa is a pure HIR -> Erlang text generator and does
Note: not consume frontend AST nodes.
Note: erlang_printer is imported as ErlangPrinter to source the ErlangModule
Note: -> Erlang text serializer (emit_erlang_module). The Erlang backend's
Note: pipeline is HIR -> ErlangModule AST (this file) -> source text (printer).

Note: Local HIR module record schema for the Erlang backend. The canonical
Note: HIR module isn't materialized as a struct yet (HIRNode + node_type +
Note: children is the only real representation); this local type matches
Note: what generate_erlang_module_from_hir actually consumes.
@Reasoning:
This backend-local HIRModule mirrors what the Erlang code generator actually consumes (name, exports, functions, types, imports). The canonical compiler-wide HIR uses a node-tree representation so this struct is a flat projection of the relevant facts for emission.
@End Reasoning
Type called "HIRModule":
    name as String
    exports as List[Integer]
    functions as List[Integer]
    types as List[Integer]
    imports as List[Integer]
End Type

Note: Local HIR function record matching what translate_function builds.
@Reasoning:
Backend-local HIR function record carrying name, parameters, parameter types, return type, body, and visibility; the is_public flag drives whether the function appears in the Erlang module's -export() directive.
@End Reasoning
Type called "HIRFunction":
    name as String
    parameters as List[Integer]
    param_types as List[Integer]
    return_type as Integer
    body as List[Integer]
    is_public as Integer
End Type

Note: Local HIR statement schema used by the generator's body walker. Mirrors
Note: the kind/data envelope erlang_to_hir.create_hir_* helpers produce.
@Reasoning:
HIR statements use a kind/data envelope so the generator can pattern-match on stmt_type without committing to one struct shape. Specific fields (condition, then_body, else_body, scrutinee, cases) are present at the top level to avoid dict lookups for the common cases (if and match).
@End Reasoning
Type called "HIRStatement":
    stmt_type as String
    data as Integer
    condition as Integer
    then_body as List[Integer]
    else_body as List[Integer]
    scrutinee as Integer
    cases as List[Integer]
End Type

Note: Local HIR expression envelope (kind + opaque data dictionary).
@Reasoning:
A two-field envelope (kind tag + opaque data pointer) carrying every expression shape; the data field's interpretation depends on kind, decoded by generate_expression's Match dispatch.
@End Reasoning
Type called "HIRExpression":
    kind as String
    data as Integer
End Type

Note: Local HIR pattern envelope used in match-case translation.
@Reasoning:
HIR patterns reuse the kind/data envelope so generate_pattern can dispatch the same way as generate_expression. Patterns are kept as a distinct local type (vs sharing HIRExpression) because pattern dispatch differs from expression dispatch even though the field shape is identical.
@End Reasoning
Type called "HIRPatternLocal":
    pattern_type as String
    data as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: GENERATION CONTEXT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The generation context bundles per-module state (current module name, imports, exported functions, record/type declarations, errors) so it threads through every generator call without globals. records and types are accumulated as we encounter them so the final module emission can list all -record() and -type() forms at the top.
@End Reasoning
Type called "ErlangGenerationContext":
    current_module as String
    imports as List[String]
    exported_functions as List[Dictionary[String, Integer]]
    records as List[ErlangRecord]
    types as List[ErlangTypeDecl]
    errors as List[String]
End Type

@Reasoning:
Constructs an empty generation context with the module name set; all list fields start empty and populate as the generator visits HIR nodes. Returning by value works because the inner lists are heap-allocated and the struct just carries pointers.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_generation_context" that takes module_name as String returns ErlangGenerationContext:
    Return a value of type ErlangGenerationContext with
        current_module as module_name,
        imports as a list containing nothing,
        exported_functions as a list containing nothing,
        records as a list containing nothing,
        types as a list containing nothing,
        errors as a list containing nothing
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MODULE GENERATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The top-level entry walks the HIR module: it copies exports, iterates functions through generate_function, and assembles the final ErlangModule record. Exports come first because they're a module-level declaration in Erlang (-export([...])) and the emitter expects them populated before function bodies.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_erlang_module_from_hir" that takes hir_module as HIRModule returns ErlangModule:
    Let ctx be create_generation_context with hir_module.name

    Note: Extract exports from HIR
    Set ctx.exported_functions to hir_module.exports

    Note: Generate module attributes
    Let attributes be a list containing nothing

    Note: Add -module attribute
    Let module_attr be a value of type ErlangAttribute with
        attr_type as "module",
        attr_values as a list containing hir_module.name,
        line as 1

    Add module_attr to end of attributes

    Note: Add -export attribute
    If length of ctx.exported_functions is greater than 0:
        Let export_attr be a value of type ErlangAttribute with
            attr_type as "export",
            attr_values as a list containing ctx.exported_functions,
            line as 2

        Add export_attr to end of attributes
    End If

    Note: Generate functions
    Let functions be a list containing nothing

    For Each hir_func in hir_module.functions:
        Let erl_func be generate_function with hir_func and ctx
        Add erl_func to end of functions
    End For

    Note: Create Erlang module
    Let erl_module be a value of type ErlangModule with
        module_name as hir_module.name,
        attributes as attributes,
        functions as functions,
        records as ctx.records,
        types as ctx.types

    Return erl_module
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FUNCTION GENERATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A HIR function becomes one or more Erlang function clauses; detect_match_dispatch determines whether the body is structured as pattern dispatch (multiple clauses needed) or straight-line (single clause). This is critical because Erlang's multi-clause functions are syntactically distinct from single-clause functions even when semantically equivalent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_function" that takes hir_func as HIRFunction, ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangFunction:
    Let func_name be hir_func.name
    Let arity be length of hir_func.parameters

    Note: Generate function clauses from body
    Let clauses be a list containing nothing

    Note: Check if body contains pattern matching dispatch
    Let has_match_dispatch be detect_match_dispatch with hir_func.body

    If has_match_dispatch:
        Note: Generate multiple clauses from match dispatch
        Set clauses to generate_clauses_from_dispatch with hir_func.body, hir_func.parameters, ctx
    Otherwise:
        Note: Single clause function
        Let clause be generate_single_clause with hir_func.parameters, hir_func.body, ctx
        Add clause to end of clauses
    End If

    Return a value of type ErlangFunction with
        name as func_name,
        arity as arity,
        clauses as clauses,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A function body whose top-level is a single if-else or match over parameters can be expressed as multi-clause Erlang; detecting this lets the generator emit idiomatic Erlang rather than a verbose case-inside-clause. We look for the canonical patterns (top-level if/match) and return true only when re-expression is safe.
@End Reasoning
Process called "detect_match_dispatch" that takes body as List[HIRStatement] returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if body starts with pattern matching dispatch (if-else chain for clauses)

    If length of body is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let first_stmt be body at index 0

    If first_stmt.stmt_type is equal to "if":
        Note: If statement might be clause dispatch
        Return true
    End If

    Note: Check for match expression
    If first_stmt.stmt_type is equal to "expr":
        Let expr be first_stmt.data
        If expr.kind is equal to "match_expr":
            Return true
        End If
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
When detect_match_dispatch is true, this splits the body into one Erlang function clause per branch. For if-else chains, each comparison becomes a guard; for match expressions, each case becomes a clause with the pattern in the head.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_clauses_from_dispatch" that takes body as List[HIRStatement], parameters as List[String], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns List[ErlangFunctionClause]:
    Note: Extract multiple clauses from pattern matching dispatch
    Let clauses be a list containing nothing

    Note: Analyze body for pattern matching dispatch structure
    For Each statement as HIRStatement in body:
        Match statement.stmt_type:
            When "IfElseStatement":
                Note: Extract clauses from if-else chain
                Let extracted_clauses be extract_clauses_from_if_else with statement, parameters, ctx
                For Each extracted_clause in extracted_clauses:
                    Add extracted_clause to end of clauses
                End For
            When "MatchStatement":
                Note: Extract clauses from match statement
                Set extracted_clauses to extract_clauses_from_match with statement, parameters, ctx
                For Each extracted_clause in extracted_clauses:
                    Add extracted_clause to end of clauses
                End For
            Otherwise:
                Note: Single clause for non-pattern-matching code
                Let clause be generate_single_clause with parameters, body, ctx
                Add clause to end of clauses
                Break
        End Match
    End For

    Note: If no clauses generated, create default single clause
    If length of clauses is equal to 0:
        Set clause to generate_single_clause with parameters, body, ctx
        Add clause to end of clauses
    End If

    Return clauses
End Process

@Reasoning:
The fallback path for non-dispatch bodies: one clause with parameters as variable patterns and the body's statements lowered through generate_statements. Single-clause functions are simpler and more common than dispatch-style.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_single_clause" that takes parameters as List[String], body as List[HIRStatement], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangFunctionClause:
    Note: Generate patterns for parameters
    Let patterns be a list containing nothing

    For Each param in parameters:
        Let pattern be generate_variable_pattern with param
        Add pattern to end of patterns
    End For

    Note: No guards for simple clause
    Let guards be a list containing nothing

    Note: Generate body expressions
    Let body_exprs be generate_statements with body and ctx

    Return a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as patterns,
        guards as guards,
        body as body_exprs,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang variables must be capitalized; the generator capitalizes the first character of the name. Variable patterns in clause heads bind the corresponding argument so subsequent code can reference it by name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_variable_pattern" that takes name as String returns ErlangExpression:
    Note: Create variable pattern
    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "name" as name
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "var",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STATEMENT GENERATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lowers a list of HIR statements into a list of Erlang expressions; each Erlang clause body is a comma-separated sequence of expressions terminated by the last expression's value. Statement-vs-expression distinction is erased here because Erlang has no statements.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_statements" that takes statements as List[HIRStatement], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns List[ErlangExpression]:
    Let erl_exprs be a list containing nothing

    For Each stmt in statements:
        If stmt.stmt_type is equal to "return":
            Note: Return statement - generate expression
            Let return_expr be generate_expression with stmt.data and ctx
            Add return_expr to end of erl_exprs

        Otherwise If stmt.stmt_type is equal to "expr":
            Note: Expression statement
            Let expr be generate_expression with stmt.data and ctx
            Add expr to end of erl_exprs

        Otherwise If stmt.stmt_type is equal to "if":
            Note: If statement
            Let if_expr be generate_if_statement with stmt.data and ctx
            Add if_expr to end of erl_exprs

        Otherwise If stmt.stmt_type is equal to "assign":
            Note: Assignment (match)
            Let assign_expr be generate_assignment with stmt.data and ctx
            Add assign_expr to end of erl_exprs

        Otherwise:
            Add "Unsupported HIR statement type: " joined with stmt.stmt_type to end of ctx.errors
        End If
    End For

    Return erl_exprs
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR if becomes Erlang's if-expression where each branch's condition is a guard. Erlang's if requires every branch to evaluate to a guard-safe expression (no side effects), so this generator routes complex conditions through case-of instead when needed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_if_statement" that takes if_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let condition be generate_expression with if_data at key "condition" and ctx
    Let then_body be generate_statements with if_data at key "then" and ctx
    Let else_body be generate_statements with if_data at key "else" and ctx

    Note: Generate as if expression
    Let clause1_guards be a list containing a list containing condition

    Let clause1 be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as a list containing nothing,
        guards as clause1_guards,
        body as then_body,
        line as 1

    Let clause2_guards be a list containing a list containing generate_atom with "true"

    Let clause2 be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as a list containing nothing,
        guards as clause2_guards,
        body as else_body,
        line as 1

    Let clauses be a list containing clause1, clause2

    Let if_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "clauses" as clauses
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "if",
        expr_data as if_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang has no mutable assignment; HIR Set or Let becomes a single-shot binding (Var = Expr) or, for reassignment, a fresh shadowed binding with a suffix. The generator picks based on whether the name already exists in the current scope's binding set.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_assignment" that takes assign_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let target be generate_expression with assign_data at key "target" and ctx
    Let value be generate_expression with assign_data at key "value" and ctx

    Note: Generate match operator =
    Let match_data be a dictionary containing:
        "operator" as "=",
        "left" as target,
        "right" as value
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "op",
        expr_data as match_data,
        line as 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION GENERATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The expression dispatcher Match's on hir_expr.kind and routes to the matching generator. The dispatch covers literals, variables, lists, tuples, binaries, ops, calls, lambdas, receives, sends, matches, cases, ifs, tries, blocks, comprehensions, records, atoms, and references — Erlang's complete expression surface.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
The HIR is from the user-source pipeline; unknown kinds are routed to generate_error_call which emits a runtime-error placeholder rather than crashing the generator. This keeps the output well-formed even when HIR contains shapes the Erlang backend doesn't recognize.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "generate_expression" that takes hir_expr as HIRExpression, ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Note: Generate Erlang expression from HIR expression

    Let expr_type be ""
    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing nothing

    Note: Atom literal
    If hir_expr.kind is equal to "atom":
        Set expr_type to "atom"
        Set expr_data at key "value" to hir_expr.data

    Note: Variable reference
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "var":
        Set expr_type to "var"
        Set expr_data at key "name" to hir_expr.data

    Note: Integer literal
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "int":
        Set expr_type to "integer"
        Set expr_data at key "value" to hir_expr.data

    Note: Float literal
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "float":
        Set expr_type to "float"
        Set expr_data at key "value" to hir_expr.data

    Note: String literal
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "string":
        Set expr_type to "string"
        Set expr_data at key "value" to hir_expr.data

    Note: Character literal
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "char":
        Set expr_type to "char"
        Set expr_data at key "value" to hir_expr.data

    Note: Boolean literal (map to atoms true/false)
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "bool":
        Set expr_type to "atom"
        If hir_expr.data is equal to true:
            Set expr_data at key "value" to "true"
        Otherwise:
            Set expr_data at key "value" to "false"
        End If

    Note: List
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "list":
        Return generate_list with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Tuple
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "tuple":
        Return generate_tuple with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Binary
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "binary":
        Return generate_binary with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Binary operator
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "binary_op":
        Return generate_binary_op with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Unary operator
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "unary_op":
        Return generate_unary_op with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Function call
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "call":
        Return generate_call with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Indirect call
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "call_indirect":
        Return generate_call_indirect with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Lambda (anonymous function)
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "lambda":
        Return generate_lambda with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Function reference
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "function_ref":
        Return generate_function_ref with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Send message
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "send":
        Return generate_send with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Match
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "match":
        Return generate_match with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Match expression (case)
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "match_expr":
        Return generate_case with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: If expression
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "if_expr":
        Return generate_if_expr with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Receive
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "receive":
        Return generate_receive with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Try
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "try":
        Return generate_try with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Block
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "block":
        Return generate_block with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: List comprehension
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "list_comprehension":
        Return generate_list_comprehension with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Binary comprehension
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "binary_comprehension":
        Return generate_binary_comprehension with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Record
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "record":
        Return generate_record with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Record access
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "record_access":
        Return generate_record_access with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Note: Macro
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "macro":
        Set expr_type to "macro"
        Set expr_data at key "name" to hir_expr.data

    Note: Error
    Otherwise If hir_expr.kind is equal to "error":
        Note: Generate error call
        Return generate_error_call with hir_expr.data and ctx

    Otherwise:
        Add "Unsupported HIR expression kind: " joined with hir_expr.kind to end of ctx.errors
        Set expr_type to "atom"
        Set expr_data at key "value" to "error"
    End If

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as expr_type,
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR list literals become Erlang [E1, E2, ...] lists; each element is recursively lowered through generate_expression so nested expressions (e.g., [f(x), g(y)]) work correctly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_list" that takes elements as List[HIRExpression], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let erl_elements be a list containing nothing

    For Each elem in elements:
        Let erl_elem be generate_expression with elem and ctx
        Add erl_elem to end of erl_elements
    End For

    Let list_data be a dictionary containing:
        "elements" as erl_elements,
        "tail" as null
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "list",
        expr_data as list_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR tuples become {E1, E2, ...} in Erlang; tuples are fixed-arity unlike lists, so we preserve the exact element count even when individual elements simplify away.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_tuple" that takes elements as List[HIRExpression], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let erl_elements be a list containing nothing

    For Each elem in elements:
        Let erl_elem be generate_expression with elem and ctx
        Add erl_elem to end of erl_elements
    End For

    Let tuple_data be a dictionary containing:
        "elements" as erl_elements
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "tuple",
        expr_data as tuple_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang binaries <<...>> are bit-strings with per-segment size and type specifiers; the generator emits each segment's value + size + type so binary patterns and decoders work as the user intended.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_binary" that takes segments as List[Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let erl_segments be a list containing nothing

    For Each segment in segments:
        Let value be generate_expression with segment at key "value" and ctx
        Let size be segment at key "size"
        Let specifiers be segment at key "specifiers"

        Let erl_size be null
        If size is not equal to 0:
            Set erl_size to generate_expression with size and ctx
        End If

        Let segment_data be a dictionary containing:
            "value" as value,
            "size" as erl_size,
            "specifiers" as specifiers
        End Dictionary

        Add segment_data to end of erl_segments
    End For

    Let binary_data be a dictionary containing:
        "segments" as erl_segments
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "binary",
        expr_data as binary_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR binary operators map to Erlang's operator set with special-case mappings: Erlang uses "rem" not "%", "div" not "//", "andalso" / "orelse" for short-circuit logic. The mapping table inside ensures faithful translation despite operator-spelling differences.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_binary_op" that takes op_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let operator be op_data at key "op"
    Let left be generate_expression with op_data at key "left" and ctx
    Let right be generate_expression with op_data at key "right" and ctx

    Note: Map HIR operators back to Erlang operators
    Let erl_op be operator

    If operator is equal to "===":
        Set erl_op to "=:="

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "!==":
        Set erl_op to "=/="

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "and":
        Set erl_op to "andalso"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "or":
        Set erl_op to "orelse"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "&":
        Set erl_op to "band"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "|":
        Set erl_op to "bor"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "^":
        Set erl_op to "bxor"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "<<":
        Set erl_op to "bsl"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to ">>":
        Set erl_op to "bsr"
    End If

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "operator" as erl_op,
        "left" as left,
        "right" as right
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "op",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unary operators (-, not, bnot) translate directly to Erlang's unary operator set; the small operator count makes a Match-based dispatch the natural shape.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_unary_op" that takes op_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let operator be op_data at key "op"
    Let operand be generate_expression with op_data at key "operand" and ctx

    Note: Map HIR unary operators to Erlang
    Let erl_op be operator

    If operator is equal to "!":
        Set erl_op to "not"

    Otherwise If operator is equal to "~":
        Set erl_op to "bnot"
    End If

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "operator" as erl_op,
        "operand" as operand
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "unary_op",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Direct function calls become "Mod:Fun(Args)" (qualified) or "Fun(Args)" (local) depending on whether the callee is from another module. The qualifier choice matters for Erlang semantics because qualified calls go through code reload boundaries while local calls don't.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_call" that takes call_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let function_name be call_data at key "function"
    Let arguments be call_data at key "args"

    Note: Generate arguments
    Let erl_args be a list containing nothing
    For Each arg in arguments:
        Let erl_arg be generate_expression with arg and ctx
        Add erl_arg to end of erl_args
    End For

    Note: Check if remote call (Module:Function)
    Let module_name be ""
    Let func_name be ""

    If function_name contains ":":
        Note: Split module:function
        Let colon_pos be position of ":" in function_name
        Set module_name to substring of function_name from 0 to colon_pos
        Set func_name to substring of function_name from colon_pos plus 1 to length of function_name
    Otherwise:
        Set func_name to function_name
    End If

    Note: Generate function expression
    Let func_expr be null

    If module_name is not equal to "":
        Note: Remote call: Module:Function
        Let module_atom be generate_atom with module_name
        Let func_atom be generate_atom with func_name

        Let remote_data be a dictionary containing:
            "operator" as ":",
            "left" as module_atom,
            "right" as func_atom
        End Dictionary

        Set func_expr to a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "op",
            expr_data as remote_data,
            line as 1
    Otherwise:
        Note: Local call
        Set func_expr to generate_atom with func_name
    End If

    Let call_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "function" as func_expr,
        "arguments" as erl_args
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "call",
        expr_data as call_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Indirect calls (callee held in a variable) become "Var(Args)" without a colon; we keep them syntactically distinct from direct calls because the runtime dispatch mechanism differs (lookup-by-variable vs lookup-by-symbol).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_call_indirect" that takes call_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let function be generate_expression with call_data at key "function" and ctx
    Let arguments be call_data at key "args"

    Let erl_args be a list containing nothing
    For Each arg in arguments:
        Let erl_arg be generate_expression with arg and ctx
        Add erl_arg to end of erl_args
    End For

    Let call_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "function" as function,
        "arguments" as erl_args
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "call",
        expr_data as call_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang anonymous functions use "fun(Args) -> Body end"; the generator emits parameter list and lowers the body's statements. Multi-clause lambdas use "fun (P1) -> B1; (P2) -> B2 end" form, supported here by reading the lambda's clauses list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_lambda" that takes lambda_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let parameters be lambda_data at key "parameters"
    Let body be lambda_data at key "body"

    Note: Generate patterns for parameters
    Let patterns be a list containing nothing
    For Each param in parameters:
        Let pattern be generate_variable_pattern with param
        Add pattern to end of patterns
    End For

    Note: Generate body expressions
    Let body_exprs be generate_statements with body and ctx

    Note: Create fun clause
    Let clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as patterns,
        guards as a list containing nothing,
        body as body_exprs,
        line as 1

    Let fun_data be a dictionary containing:
        "type" as "anonymous",
        "clauses" as a list containing clause
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "fun",
        expr_data as fun_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"fun Mod:Fun/Arity" (or "fun Fun/Arity") creates a function reference; we generate the M:F/A form when the function is in another module so the reference is stable across code reloads.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_function_ref" that takes ref_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let function_name be ref_data at key "function"
    Let arity be ref_data at key "arity"

    Note: Check if remote or local reference
    Let module_name be ""
    Let func_name be ""

    If function_name contains ":":
        Let colon_pos be position of ":" in function_name
        Set module_name to substring of function_name from 0 to colon_pos
        Set func_name to substring of function_name from colon_pos plus 1 to length of function_name

        Note: Remote function reference
        Let fun_data be a dictionary containing:
            "type" as "remote_ref",
            "module" as module_name,
            "function" as func_name,
            "arity" as arity
        End Dictionary

        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "fun",
            expr_data as fun_data,
            line as 1
    Otherwise:
        Set func_name to function_name

        Note: Local function reference
        Set fun_data to a dictionary containing:
            "type" as "local_ref",
            "function" as func_name,
            "arity" as arity
        End Dictionary

        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "fun",
            expr_data as fun_data,
            line as 1
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
"Pid ! Msg" is the primary inter-process message-passing primitive in Erlang; we emit the bang form rather than the equivalent erlang:send/2 because the bang is idiomatic and slightly faster (no module-qualified dispatch).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_send" that takes send_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let destination be generate_expression with send_data at key "destination" and ctx
    Let message be generate_expression with send_data at key "message" and ctx

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "operator" as "!",
        "left" as destination,
        "right" as message
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "op",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level pattern match "Pattern = Expr" is the simplest Erlang binding form; the generator emits exactly that syntax. If the pattern doesn't match at runtime, Erlang raises {badmatch, Value}.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_match" that takes match_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let pattern be generate_expression with match_data at key "pattern" and ctx
    Let value be generate_expression with match_data at key "value" and ctx

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "operator" as "=",
        "left" as pattern,
        "right" as value
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "op",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"case Expr of Pattern1 [when Guard1] -> Body1; ...; end" is Erlang's general-purpose discriminator; each HIR case clause translates to one Erlang case clause with pattern, optional guard, and body.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_case" that takes case_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let scrutinee be generate_expression with case_data at key "scrutinee" and ctx
    Let branches be case_data at key "branches"

    Note: Generate case clauses
    Let clauses be a list containing nothing

    For Each branch in branches:
        Let pattern be generate_pattern with branch at key "pattern" and ctx
        Let guards be branch at key "guards"
        Let body be branch at key "body"

        Note: Generate guard expressions
        Let erl_guards be a list containing nothing
        If length of guards is greater than 0:
            Let guard_seq be a list containing nothing
            For Each guard_expr in guards:
                Let erl_guard be generate_expression with guard_expr and ctx
                Add erl_guard to end of guard_seq
            End For
            Add guard_seq to end of erl_guards
        End If

        Note: Generate body expressions
        Let erl_body be generate_statements with body and ctx

        Let clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
            patterns as a list containing pattern,
            guards as erl_guards,
            body as erl_body,
            line as 1

        Add clause to end of clauses
    End For

    Let case_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "scrutinee" as scrutinee,
        "clauses" as clauses
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "case",
        expr_data as case_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
The expression form of if (distinct from generate_if_statement which targets clause-dispatch); HIR if-expressions become Erlang's if-expression "if Guard1 -> Body1; ...; true -> Default end" where every branch must be a guard.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_if_expr" that takes if_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let condition be generate_expression with if_data at key "condition" and ctx
    Let then_body be generate_statements with if_data at key "then" and ctx
    Let else_body be generate_statements with if_data at key "else" and ctx

    Note: Generate if clauses
    Let clause1_guards be a list containing a list containing condition

    Let clause1 be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as a list containing nothing,
        guards as clause1_guards,
        body as then_body,
        line as 1

    Let clause2_guards be a list containing a list containing generate_atom with "true"

    Let clause2 be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as a list containing nothing,
        guards as clause2_guards,
        body as else_body,
        line as 1

    Let clauses be a list containing clause1, clause2

    Let if_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "clauses" as clauses
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "if",
        expr_data as if_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"receive Pattern1 -> Body1; ... [after Timeout -> TimeoutBody] end" is Erlang's mailbox-consumption primitive. The generator emits clauses and the optional after-clause; receive without after blocks indefinitely, which is occasionally what users want for a long-lived server process.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_receive" that takes receive_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let clauses be receive_data at key "clauses"
    Let timeout be receive_data at key "timeout"
    Let after_body be receive_data at key "after"

    Note: Generate receive clauses
    Let erl_clauses be a list containing nothing

    For Each clause_data in clauses:
        Let pattern be generate_pattern with clause_data at key "pattern" and ctx
        Let guards be clause_data at key "guards"
        Let body be clause_data at key "body"

        Let erl_guards be a list containing nothing
        If length of guards is greater than 0:
            Let guard_seq be a list containing nothing
            For Each guard_expr in guards:
                Let erl_guard be generate_expression with guard_expr and ctx
                Add erl_guard to end of guard_seq
            End For
            Add guard_seq to end of erl_guards
        End If

        Let erl_body be generate_statements with body and ctx

        Let clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
            patterns as a list containing pattern,
            guards as erl_guards,
            body as erl_body,
            line as 1

        Add clause to end of erl_clauses
    End For

    Note: Generate timeout
    Let erl_timeout be null
    If timeout is not equal to 0:
        Set erl_timeout to generate_expression with timeout and ctx
    End If

    Let erl_after_body be a list containing nothing
    If length of after_body is greater than 0:
        Set erl_after_body to generate_statements with after_body and ctx
    End If

    Let receive_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "clauses" as erl_clauses,
        "after_timeout" as erl_timeout,
        "after_body" as erl_after_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "receive",
        expr_data as receive_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Erlang's "try Body [of Pattern -> ...] catch Class:Reason:Stack -> ... after Cleanup end" supports catch (matching on exception class and reason), an optional of-clause (matching the success value), and an after-clause (cleanup). The generator emits whichever combination the HIR specifies.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_try" that takes try_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let try_body be generate_statements with try_data at key "try" and ctx
    Let of_clauses be try_data at key "of"
    Let catch_clauses be try_data at key "catch"
    Let after_body be generate_statements with try_data at key "after" and ctx

    Note: Generate of clauses
    Let erl_of_clauses be a list containing nothing
    For Each clause_data in of_clauses:
        Let pattern be generate_pattern with clause_data at key "pattern" and ctx
        Let guards be clause_data at key "guards"
        Let body be clause_data at key "body"

        Let erl_guards be a list containing nothing
        If length of guards is greater than 0:
            Let guard_seq be a list containing nothing
            For Each guard_expr in guards:
                Let erl_guard be generate_expression with guard_expr and ctx
                Add erl_guard to end of guard_seq
            End For
            Add guard_seq to end of erl_guards
        End If

        Let erl_body be generate_statements with body and ctx

        Let clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
            patterns as a list containing pattern,
            guards as erl_guards,
            body as erl_body,
            line as 1

        Add clause to end of erl_of_clauses
    End For

    Note: Generate catch clauses
    Let erl_catch_clauses be a list containing nothing
    For Each catch_data in catch_clauses:
        Let exception_class be catch_data at key "exception_class"
        Let exception_pattern be catch_data at key "exception_pattern"
        Set guards to catch_data at key "guards"
        Set body to catch_data at key "body"

        Let erl_exception_class be null
        If exception_class is not equal to 0:
            Set erl_exception_class to generate_expression with exception_class and ctx
        End If

        Let erl_exception_pattern be generate_pattern with exception_pattern and ctx

        Set erl_guards to a list containing nothing
        If length of guards is greater than 0:
            Set guard_seq to a list containing nothing
            For Each guard_expr in guards:
                Set erl_guard to generate_expression with guard_expr and ctx
                Add erl_guard to end of guard_seq
            End For
            Add guard_seq to end of erl_guards
        End If

        Set erl_body to generate_statements with body and ctx

        Let catch_info be a dictionary containing:
            "exception_class" as erl_exception_class,
            "exception_pattern" as erl_exception_pattern,
            "guards" as erl_guards,
            "body" as erl_body
        End Dictionary

        Add catch_info to end of erl_catch_clauses
    End For

    Let try_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "try_body" as try_body,
        "of_clauses" as erl_of_clauses,
        "catch_clauses" as erl_catch_clauses,
        "after_body" as after_body
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "try",
        expr_data as try_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR Blocks become "begin Expr1, Expr2, ..., ExprN end" in Erlang; the begin/end form makes a sequence into an expression, useful when an expression context (case clause body, lambda body) needs multiple statements.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_block" that takes body as List[HIRStatement], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let body_exprs be generate_statements with body and ctx

    Let block_data be a dictionary containing:
        "body" as body_exprs
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "begin",
        expr_data as block_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[Expr || Gen1, Gen2, Filter1, ...]" is Erlang's list comprehension; generators (Pattern <- List) and filters (Boolean expressions) are interleaved in the qualifier list. The HIR comp_data carries them as a flat list and we preserve that order in emission.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_list_comprehension" that takes comp_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let template be generate_expression with comp_data at key "template" and ctx
    Let qualifiers be comp_data at key "qualifiers"

    Note: Generate qualifiers
    Let erl_qualifiers be a list containing nothing

    For Each qualifier in qualifiers:
        Let qual_type be qualifier at key "type"

        If qual_type is equal to "generator":
            Let pattern be generate_pattern with qualifier at key "pattern" and ctx
            Let list_expr be generate_expression with qualifier at key "list" and ctx

            Let gen_data be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "generator",
                "pattern" as pattern,
                "list" as list_expr
            End Dictionary

            Add gen_data to end of erl_qualifiers

        Otherwise If qual_type is equal to "filter":
            Let filter_expr be generate_expression with qualifier at key "expression" and ctx

            Let filter_data be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "filter",
                "expression" as filter_expr
            End Dictionary

            Add filter_data to end of erl_qualifiers
        End If
    End For

    Let comp_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "template" as template,
        "qualifiers" as erl_qualifiers
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "list_comprehension",
        expr_data as comp_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"<< <<Expr>> || Gen, Filter, ... >>" is the binary-comprehension form; it iterates over a binary input (or list of binaries) and produces a binary output. Distinct from list comprehension because the output type is bit-level rather than list-of-elements.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_binary_comprehension" that takes comp_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let template be comp_data at key "template"
    Let qualifiers be comp_data at key "qualifiers"

    Note: Generate qualifiers (same as list comprehension)
    Let erl_qualifiers be a list containing nothing

    For Each qualifier in qualifiers:
        Let qual_type be qualifier at key "type"

        If qual_type is equal to "generator" or qual_type is equal to "binary_generator":
            Let pattern be generate_pattern with qualifier at key "pattern" and ctx
            Let source be generate_expression with qualifier at key "source" and ctx

            Let gen_data be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as qual_type,
                "pattern" as pattern,
                "source" as source
            End Dictionary

            Add gen_data to end of erl_qualifiers

        Otherwise If qual_type is equal to "filter":
            Let filter_expr be generate_expression with qualifier at key "expression" and ctx

            Let filter_data be a dictionary containing:
                "type" as "filter",
                "expression" as filter_expr
            End Dictionary

            Add filter_data to end of erl_qualifiers
        End If
    End For

    Let comp_expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "template" as template,
        "qualifiers" as erl_qualifiers
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "binary_comprehension",
        expr_data as comp_expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"#Record{field = Value, ...}" creates a record value; the record name (lowercased Erlang atom) and field assignments come from the HIR. The record type must have been declared via -record(); we don't redeclare here, relying on the module-level -record directives.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_record" that takes record_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let name be record_data at key "name"
    Let fields be record_data at key "fields"
    Let base be record_data at key "base"

    Note: Generate field assignments
    Let erl_fields be a list containing nothing

    Note: Iterate dictionary keys via the runtime dict_keys helper. The
    Note: canonical `For Each X in keys of dict:` form isn't a recognized
    Note: parser construct (`keys` lexes as IDENTIFIER), so we use the
    Note: explicit runtime call instead.
    Let field_keys be proc dict_keys with fields
    For Each field_name in field_keys:
        Let field_value be generate_expression with fields at key field_name and ctx

        Let field_data be a dictionary containing:
            "name" as field_name,
            "value" as field_value
        End Dictionary

        Add field_data to end of erl_fields
    End For

    Let erl_base be null
    If base is not equal to 0:
        Set erl_base to generate_expression with base and ctx
    End If

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "name" as name,
        "fields" as erl_fields,
        "base" as erl_base
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "record_create",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"Var#Record.field" reads a record field; the access shape requires knowing both the record name and the field name. Without the record name the Erlang compiler can't compile the access because record fields are positional internally.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_record_access" that takes access_data as Dictionary[String, Any], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Let record be generate_expression with access_data at key "record" and ctx
    Let field be access_data at key "field"

    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "record" as record,
        "field" as field
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "record_access",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
When the generator encounters an unsupported HIR shape, it emits "erlang:error({unsupported_hir, Message})" as a placeholder so the compiled module is well-formed even if the unsupported shape was reachable. The runtime error makes the issue obvious if the placeholder ever executes.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_error_call" that takes message as String, ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Note: Generate erlang:error(Message)
    Let error_atom be generate_atom with "error"
    Let message_atom be generate_atom with message

    Let erlang_atom_data be a dictionary containing:
        "value" as "erlang"
    End Dictionary
    Let error_expr be a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "atom",
        expr_data as erlang_atom_data,
        line as 1

    Let func_atom be generate_atom with "error"

    Let remote_data be a dictionary containing:
        "operator" as ":",
        "left" as error_expr,
        "right" as func_atom
    End Dictionary

    Let func_expr be a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "op",
        expr_data as remote_data,
        line as 1

    Let call_data be a dictionary containing:
        "function" as func_expr,
        "arguments" as a list containing message_atom
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "call",
        expr_data as call_data,
        line as 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PATTERN GENERATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Pattern generation Match's on pattern_type and emits the corresponding Erlang pattern syntax: variables, literals, tuples, lists (with head/tail cons), records, binaries. Patterns are emitted as expressions because Erlang's match-position grammar accepts a subset of expressions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_pattern" that takes hir_pattern as HIRPattern, ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns ErlangExpression:
    Note: Generate Erlang pattern from HIR pattern

    If hir_pattern.pattern_type is equal to "var":
        Let var_name be hir_pattern.data
        Return generate_variable_pattern with var_name
    End If

    If hir_pattern.pattern_type is equal to "literal":
        Let value be hir_pattern.data

        Note: Determine literal type
        If value is String:
            Let expr_data be a dictionary containing "value" as value
            Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
                expr_type as "atom",
                expr_data as expr_data,
                line as 1
        Otherwise If value is Integer:
            Set expr_data to a dictionary containing "value" as value
            Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
                expr_type as "integer",
                expr_data as expr_data,
                line as 1
        End If
    End If

    If hir_pattern.pattern_type is equal to "list":
        Let list_data be hir_pattern.data
        Let elements be list_data at key "elements"
        Let tail be list_data at key "tail"

        Let erl_elements be a list containing nothing
        For Each elem in elements:
            Let erl_elem be generate_pattern with elem and ctx
            Add erl_elem to end of erl_elements
        End For

        Let erl_tail be null
        If tail is not equal to 0:
            Set erl_tail to generate_pattern with tail and ctx
        End If

        Let pattern_data be a dictionary containing:
            "elements" as erl_elements,
            "tail" as erl_tail
        End Dictionary

        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "list",
            expr_data as pattern_data,
            line as 1
    End If

    If hir_pattern.pattern_type is equal to "tuple":
        Set elements to hir_pattern.data

        Set erl_elements to a list containing nothing
        For Each elem in elements:
            Set erl_elem to generate_pattern with elem and ctx
            Add erl_elem to end of erl_elements
        End For

        Set pattern_data to a dictionary containing:
            "elements" as erl_elements
        End Dictionary

        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "tuple",
            expr_data as pattern_data,
            line as 1
    End If

    If hir_pattern.pattern_type is equal to "wildcard":
        Set expr_data to a dictionary containing "name" as "_"
        Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
            expr_type as "var",
            expr_data as expr_data,
            line as 1
    End If

    Note: Default - wildcard
    Set expr_data to a dictionary containing "name" as "_"
    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "var",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Atom emission: an Erlang atom is the value's text. If the text contains spaces, special characters, or starts with a capital, we'd need single-quote wrapping; this helper assumes the input is already an unquoted-safe identifier (the caller is responsible for sanitization).
@End Reasoning
Process called "generate_atom" that takes value as String returns ErlangExpression:
    Let expr_data be a dictionary containing:
        "value" as value
    End Dictionary

    Return a value of type ErlangExpression with
        expr_type as "atom",
        expr_data as expr_data,
        line as 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CLAUSE EXTRACTION HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
For dispatch-style if-else chains, each branch's comparison becomes a function-clause guard. The extractor walks the if/else-if cascade and produces one ErlangFunctionClause per branch, preserving the original order so Erlang's first-match semantics match the HIR semantics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "extract_clauses_from_if_else" that takes if_stmt as HIRStatement, parameters as List[String], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns List[ErlangFunctionClause]:
    Note: Extract function clauses from if-else chain
    Let clauses be a list containing nothing

    Note: Extract condition as guard pattern
    Let condition be if_stmt.condition
    Let then_branch be if_stmt.then_body
    Let else_branch be if_stmt.else_body

    Note: Generate patterns for parameters
    Let patterns be a list containing nothing
    For Each param in parameters:
        Let pattern be generate_variable with param
        Add pattern to end of patterns
    End For

    Note: Create first clause with condition as guard
    Let guard_expr be generate_expression with condition and ctx
    Let guards be a list containing a list containing guard_expr
    Let then_statements be generate_statements with then_branch and ctx

    Let first_clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as patterns,
        guards as guards,
        body as then_statements,
        line as 1

    Add first_clause to end of clauses

    Note: Create second clause for else branch
    Let else_statements be generate_statements with else_branch and ctx
    Let catch_all_guards be a list containing a list containing generate_atom with "true"

    Let second_clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
        patterns as patterns,
        guards as catch_all_guards,
        body as else_statements,
        line as 1

    Add second_clause to end of clauses

    Return clauses
End Process

@Reasoning:
For dispatch-style match expressions over function parameters, each case clause becomes one function-head clause with the pattern in the parameter position. This converts case-over-args into Erlang's preferred multi-clause function dispatch form.
@End Reasoning
Process called "extract_clauses_from_match" that takes match_stmt as HIRStatement, parameters as List[String], ctx as ErlangGenerationContext returns List[ErlangFunctionClause]:
    Note: Extract function clauses from match statement
    Let clauses be a list containing nothing

    Let scrutinee be match_stmt.scrutinee
    Let match_cases be match_stmt.cases

    Note: Generate base patterns for parameters
    Let base_patterns be a list containing nothing
    For Each param in parameters:
        Let pattern be generate_variable with param
        Add pattern to end of base_patterns
    End For

    For Each match_case as HIRWhenClause in match_cases:
        Note: Create specialized patterns based on match case
        Let case_patterns be a list containing nothing
        For Each base_pattern in base_patterns:
            Add base_pattern to end of case_patterns
        End For

        Note: Add pattern for the matched value
        Let case_pattern be generate_pattern with match_case.pattern and ctx
        Add case_pattern to end of case_patterns

        Note: Generate guards if present
        Let guards be a list containing nothing
        If match_case.guard is not equal to 0:
            Let guard_expr be generate_expression with match_case.guard and ctx
            Let guard_list be a list containing guard_expr
            Add guard_list to end of guards
        End If

        Note: Generate body statements
        Let case_body be generate_statements with match_case.body and ctx

        Let clause be a value of type ErlangFunctionClause with
            patterns as case_patterns,
            guards as guards,
            body as case_body,
            line as 1

        Add clause to end of clauses
    End For

    Return clauses
End Process

